i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Schaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: occupational name for a herdsman, from Middle High German <i>schāf</i>, <i>schāp</i> ‘sheep’."],"variants":[{"name":"Schaaf","meanings":["German: variant of   Schaf  .","Dutch: metonymic occupational name for a carpenter, from <i>schaaf</i> ‘plane’. Compare   Vanderschaaf   2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Schaw was born in 1275, in Scotland, his father, John de la Schaw, was 25 and his mother, Margaret, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William De La Schaw. He lived in Land, Oppland, Norway in 1297. He died in 1323, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1275–1323":"1275–1323","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1323–1393":"1323–1393","1250–1296":"1250–1296","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1323":"1323","1278":"1278","1275":"1275","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1393":"1393"," Schaw and Hollie (the highlands near Edinburgh) Scotland":"Land, Oppland, Norra","Scotland":"Scotland","Greenock, Inverclyde, Renfrew, Scotland":"Greenock, Inverclyde, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1275–1323":"1275–1323","1278–Female":"1278–